segments.text: He was on the second floor of the YMCA building.
And Rutter was in the Koch building,
I guess, yeah, I guess through my senior year and then it was the next year that he moved up to the administration building because he became president of both the system and the college.
As far as an undergraduate student in those days was concerned, who was the most active student administrator?
Was it Dean Hannigan or was it the core commandant?
I'd say as a student administrator, I would have listed Hannigan.
The commandant was strictly business, core business.
I don't think you would have gone there for a general purpose.
I wouldn't have.
Now, they had attack officers part of that time, and a man named Calvin Reese, class of 49, was one of those.
He was also the drill team advisor, and he was absolutely my mentor and is why I graduated, and very close contact, you know, forever with him.
Describe him, then.
Well, he was a captain in the Air Force Reserve,
had kind of a very soft family farm kind of look and attitude, soft spoken.
not formal in military appearance, just extremely polite, extremely caring, but would listen and listen and listen and listen and let you come out with anything you wanted to come out with.
And because of the Drill Team Connect, you know, I started going home for supper and
Practically grew up with his young kids and just became a very major figure.
Was totally influential in my finally having enough grade points to graduate.
Did he give you some important advice?
If so, summarize it.
I can't verbally, nothing strikes me immediately, but what I got out of him was a soft mentoring relationship, role model of doing what's right, and no pretentiousness.
at all.
Were you aware of that impression then?
I was then and have seen it better as time goes along.
Right.
That first year, how did you register for classes and what was your?
You went through Sabisa Dining Hall and I think they, my memory is as a senior, I worked for housing or the Corps or somebody.
And I was at one of the central tables where everybody had to go through, hand in something or collect something, I don't know what.
And I'd just got my senior ring at the start of the fall of my senior year, first week in September.
And of course, reversed, it meant that the star was on the inside where your little finger is.
Well, I'd had it three days or something.
I shook hands with every single person that came through there.
At the end of the day, the star was embedded in my little finger, and it wasn't perfectly clear to me if it was going to ever come out.
But, you know, you just lined up behind placards and saw some, you know, old guy named Monroe teaching history, and you wished that you could get in his class instead of Garland Bayless's class.
But I wasn't so lucky.
And I hope Garland hears this.
What was your major?
Do you remember that first year?
I started pre-law, and then I went management, graduated management.
Dan Lowe helped me graduate.
Who were some of those first, in the first year, who were some of the instructors you can remember?
Oh, I don't know about the first year.
I think Garland was my history prof.
There was a man named Clark who was biology.
Were there some courses that quickly y'all were warned to stay clear of?
Some tough.
I wasn't warned enough.
I got all those classes.
And what did the routine seem like at A&M compared to what you had known at San Jacinto High School?
It was busy, very busy.
I wasn't a good student in high school.
But I probably studied zero in high school.
And so even at A&M you had to study some.
I studied very little.
I was excellent at procrastinating and thinking that I would do something and staying busy doing other things.
Right, so you left school and then came back in the fall of 60, actually it was the spring of 63.
Made out a year and a half.
Okay.
And had, I don't remember how many, I had at least 15 or 20 hours or something that I transferred from the University of Houston.
And, you know, I hung around a sea from that point.
As a result of being away for three semesters, was there any core identifier?
Zero.
Okay.
I've heard of frogs being transfers.
Well, but the key was I finished the entire freshman year.
Okay.
And so I wouldn't...
Most people, there are a few people that know now, but most of the people in Class 65 assumed that I had been with them all the way.
But a lot of guys in 64, while I was in school, knew that I had been with them.
And it wasn't said very often, but I think I had a slightly different status.
And then because of the relationship with Calvin Reese,
At the start of that spring semester, they had lost one or two sophomore advisors to the drill team.
And so I just became a sophomore advisor, one of three or four people.
And then I was plugged back in again.
And then lo and behold, the next year, I was the only junior advisor and then the only senior advisor.
And you made the decision to identify with 65 instead of 64.
Yes.
Well, it was sort of Reese's advice and the Commandant's advice.
But I mean, you could have done the... Yeah, you could have probably gone back to F2, but you'd have been out of whack, I think.
Like I learned to my pleasant surprise from Porter Garner, Jr., that he, in the class of 45, was one of those that left early.
You remember they went on trimester and all.
He never came back.
and did not have quite enough hours to officially be a senior, but that because they were shipped out early, their entire group was given their senior rings, and that he never graduated.
I had no problems.
You know, I knew...
I knew Frank Mueller, who was our student body president, was still very active, distinguished alumnus.
I knew Ted Hopgood, who I hired as commandant to come back here.
And there were just never any problems.
I've been a co-class agent for Class of 65 for 10 years with Mueller and Bill Gimmons.
And it's worked.
For my personality and what I was doing, I think I had an advantage.
What were the great advantages of being a senior in those days in the Corps?
You had whatever freedom you needed or wanted as related to what you were doing with your personal time.
You had the whatever ROTC or core functions things to do, but you basically had your own space in which to do that.

It wasn't as common back then, but I wore my boots virtually every day, you know, that that was just something, you know, I was drill team, and so I think that, you know, I wore the uniform pretty well, and so that was something that I did most of the time.
Where'd you get your boots, and how much did they cost?
They were Horlicks boots, and I don't know where we got the $95, but we got the $95.
Do you still have them?
Still have them.
Mother kept them, and so now I have them back.
The Aggie ring was $32.50.
And the myth existed then as it still exists that former students pays for half the rain.
And as far as I know, it's untrue.
But that's what people think.
And you, like many of the rest of us, were not blessed with great family wealth.
About how much extra spending money did you have in those student days?
I went to school for $500 a semester.
About $450 was room, board, tuition, books.
So I had $50 spending money.
And then I was on contract, so I got $25 a month.
And so that was all foo-foo money.
I got $20 a month from my father in the divorce situation.
And I didn't have a car.
I didn't have any vehicles.
So I was riding with people.
And I don't remember.
I was pinching pennies, but I don't remember having a problem.
Where did you and your buddies go if you wanted to have a good time?
You mean away?
Well, most of the time we would go back home.
We'd go to Houston.
I had buddies that were in Houston.
If you were going to stay here in the Brazos County area, where was a good Friday night or Saturday?
You would just go to the show and go eat and tell stories.
Where would you eat?
There would be occasional beer busts on the Brazos River, but I
I graduated from Texas A&M without having to drink beer, and it was okay that I didn't go to the beer bust.
And so I usually did not go.
Were people going to the clay pits when you were?
That's basically the way I knew it.
And as far as you know, where was that?
I'd be danged if I know.
I don't know.
I'm not sure.
Did you ever go to Uncle Ed's?
No.
Was it still going then?
Hard Liquor's?
I'm not sure those were still going.
I think Ralph's Pizza Place was going.
I didn't go to those places.
Sparky's, was it there yet?
I didn't drink beer, so I didn't go.
And I didn't have the money to do anything extra, so I didn't go.
In your outfit, as far as you knew, was there much alcohol in the dormitory?
I have no significant recall of that.
You couldn't say no, that there wasn't any.
But if there was, it would have been probably hard liquor because refrigeration and all those issues.
Everybody didn't have an icebox, a little refrigerator.
Did you and your colleagues even know the terminology of drugs?
I didn't.
I don't think so.
I don't think in the early 60s any of us
Had heard of heroin and so forth.
Not really.
And so folks smoked cigarettes?
Yeah, a lot of people smoked cigarettes.
Cigars a little?
Occasionally.
I didn't smoke.
Did anybody smoke a pipe?
Occasionally.
Yeah, I can remember a couple of guys that smoked a pipe.
I had some juniors next to me when I was a fish that smoked a pipe, and it smelled good.
In all of your undergraduate days, who were some of the memorable teachers, advisors?
Well, I've already talked about Calvin Reese and James Hannigan.
Denzel Baker was a good person.
He was commandant.
I knew Charlie Hornstein, who was a tech officer.
I knew Bill Presnell.

The Dan Lowe was the assistant dean of the College of Business and was like the typical style of the associate dean in those days in the 60s and to about mid 70s that there were very few rules written
and they would cut you slack if they thought that you were deserving of it, and would work with you to get over whatever humps were there.
I think they were very listening, very empathetic, stick to a rule if they thought it was right, but bend it a little bit if they thought that was right.
And it didn't take a lot of pressure
You know, that would happen, I think, with an individual student talking to them.
You know, Mother didn't call, you know, in the 60s.
There wasn't anybody ringing anybody's phone in the 60s.
It was the student talking to the, and so you needed people that would listen to the student.
Among my concern, I don't know.
Beckham, John Beckham.
Describe.
People like that.
Did you know John?
I knew John.
Describe him.
A tall, professional-looking professor, very professorial, with that huge, booming voice.
Incredible, deep, booming voice.
Did the students give him a nickname?
I don't remember.
Because I've always thought it should have been Daddy Deep Throat.
Yeah.
I don't remember.
Did you take a course from him?
How did you get acquainted with him?
Well, I know I knew him after I came back here in 68 very well.
I don't recall for sure as a student.
Because, see, I knew him at church and then.

working registration, he was always one of the... Judge Stewart was a prof, taught law, you know, was reported to be an alcoholic or had alcoholic problems, but was also reported to be the quality of lawyer of Percy Forman, you know, who was a major, very major lawyer, national scope, you know, during that time period in the 60s.
And his classes were usually colorful and interesting, you know, very interesting.
There was a guy named Satch Elkins who taught over there.
George Rice, who was also very helpful to me in graduating, who taught management.
So you changed business.
Was that your major?
From pre-law.
From pre-law.
Yeah, I'd stayed in business after.
I think I only changed the once.
Mm-hmm.
Let's see, anybody in English you recall?
Well, you remember the little quiet gentleman.
Cofer?
No, the little guy that lived to be pretty elderly, was around here well into his 80s, little bitty guy.
Not Tommy Mayo.
No.
He was involved in Opus, very soft-spoken, white-headed.
We'll think of his name when we edit it.
It'll hit me in a minute.
Well, it'll come back.
What about math?
No, I didn't have any good math profs.
And you mentioned Garland.
You had history.
I think I had Garland for history.
Garland.
Goveron?
I don't remember.
No Blue Book Benton?
No, I didn't have Blue Book Benton.
I think the guy's name was Luther.
He was in economics.
I had ECO 311 with him.
He was hard.
I would say now I think he was fair, but he appeared to be very hard.
So your major extracurricular activity was the drill team.
As far as you were aware, what were the expected rules of classroom conduct and behavior at A&M?
Go to class, be polite, take notes.
Was the grading fair?
No.
I think it was.
We were on the three-point system, which I think is pretty significant, because a 69 was an F. And I think an 83 was a C. So it would be different.
I wouldn't have had my same level of grade point problems if a D had even given you one grade point.
It wouldn't have been quite as tight.
And so it wasn't hard to get an F. I didn't have the feeling that they did much curving.
How did you and your buddies feel about those changes that came in the mid-60s regarding compulsory core, racial integration, co-education, and so forth?
You know, on the surface, it was like, oh, gee, this is, you know, a new army.
You know, you sort of would like for it to not happen.
And I remember we, you know, I think we marched on General Rutter's house twice for both decisions.
And, you know, it was after Chow and Duncan.
And he came out on the front porch and said, thank you for your advice and go home.
And everybody saluted and said, you know, yes, sir.
And that was it.
The riot was over.
But
I don't remember great animosity.
It was certainly conversation.
Neil Keltner was a corps commander and was somebody that I knew and bumped into occasionally.
And he was going to Austin with Rutter regularly, you know, that legislative session in representing the issues.
And so I knew that that was happening.
Which of the changes caused the greatest concern?
Was it the corps or women?
Frankly, women was first, so I think I would say women.
And then core, you're already, you know, you're right on the edge of the Vietnam business, getting ready to fire up pretty big.
I don't think people realized the full impact of the decision right at that minute.
Do you remember any event
relating to the admission of black students?
I don't.
I remember seeing a couple of those first guys in the early 60s, but I don't remember it ever being an issue.
I don't remember a single incident.
I don't know of any.
That was handled with great...
I believe A&M did that as well as any school in the country.
I'm unaware of it ever being an issue.
Of course, there weren't very many of them.
No, but still, it happened gradually and happened with great...
Well, as it turns out, the Corps was essentially first in going female, too.
You know, after that decision was made, they went female in 74.
And only the last three years has VMI and the Citadel gone that way.
And the military academies were after 74.
So we were really first in that regard.
It still struggled a long time, and there's always some bumps.
But as far as saying, yeah, it's the right thing to do, that was done pretty quickly.

And I've learned in these interviews that one of the things that Earl Rutter told Ford Albritton and John Lindsay on a trip to Chicago when they asked, well, what do we do if something happens to you, Earl?
And he first said, well, I don't have anybody, and I've got to do that.
That night they brought the subject back up.
And he said, I've been thinking about it since you brought it up this afternoon.
If something ever happened to me, you go to Tennessee and you get Jack Williams, first commissioner of higher education.
And among the things he reminded him of is that he was at Clemson, a separate land-grant school in the South.
When the changes were made.
When the changes were made.
And he went through that so he would be able to understand the culture here more clearly than most people would.
Well, after graduation...
I had two years of active duty.
I was fortunate enough to be in Germany.
I was in armor.
And I was almost literally, I was one of the last 15 guys to go to Europe instead of Vietnam.
And then you had almost no one, you know, go to Europe for a couple of years.
And the good news of that was we had 10 officers when you're supposed to have 32 in an armor battalion.
And as a second lieutenant, I was the only staff officer officially, the adjutant.
And then as a first lieutenant, I was headquarters company commander, which was the hardest job because you had all the wild people.
But had tremendous experience, but did decide to get out.
And my mentor, Calvin Reese, was leaving.
We were corresponding, writing.
And he said, I think General Rudder will give you my job if you want it.
And of course, when you change your mind and you're in Germany, a job sounds like a really good plan.
So it's just like, yeah.
So I wrote the letter.
They said, you know, touch base as soon as you get back and there might be an opening.
And I already knew Hannigan and I already knew Rutter.
And they said, fine, you know, you're hired.
You got to reach this job.
I was leaving every year.
you know, for four or five years.
It was, I was on staff.
The nature of the job that I had in the commandant's office, I was the yell leader, bonfire, fish drill team, Ross volunteer, all extra duty advisor.
Colonel McCoy was the commandant.
He didn't,
He didn't like going to any university committee meetings.
And I was somehow, at age 25, I was his senior university person over there.
And so I was going to meetings I didn't have any business being at.
But it proved to be extremely beneficial to me.
And so I saw General Rutter pretty often.
I saw Hannigan often.
The associate deans I talked about.
You know, the Beckhams and Potts and Ransdells and Lowe's and all those people were just, you know, I saw how good they were, and I was on the AOC and a lot of things.
And Dan Lowe died young, but the very first year or so, he called me one day and said,
I think he, the student was either with me or he was sending the student to see me.
Or I was sending him to see him, I don't remember which.
But anyway, we were talking and he said, I was telling him about this guy and it's like, you know, he needs a little help, you know, to graduate.
And he said, well, I think I knew somebody else like that.
Yes, I think you did.
Well, are you telling me that you think this is the guy that I should do this for over anybody else?
Yes, sir.
I think I am.
I think it'd be all right.
Then you tell him to come see me and he will graduate.
Okay.
I will.
All right.
Back in those days, you're
student days and your early days as a member of the professional staff, describe the activities of the MSC.
What role did it play?
I was never heavily connected to the MSC.
I was heavily connected to all the core things.
I knew who Stark was, but I never had any personal relationships with him.
He mostly had under his wing the real bright stars.
You know, the Corps Commander, student body president level people, people that could go to Harvard and Stanford and things like that, which we didn't have a big group.
What was his pipeline to that connection?
Former students.
No, no, no, no, no.
To get contact with those bright... Major student activities.
You know, the major chiefs.
Because I have the impression that he started identifying them first year they were here.
And he got them...
He may have.
Kind of lined up and got them.
Because it seemed to me that if you were...
It had to be activities outside of the Corps.
He wasn't going to identify you only because of Corps activities.
You've had to show up somewhere else.
With the possible exception of a Corps commander or somebody.
He would still have known who those people were.

It seemed to me that he would, in identifying, when he heard about a bright freshman, he would try to get that freshman to be the errand runner for the MSC council president or the SCONA chairman or the president of the student body and then that student would learn the ropes and they would work up and sometime later might have the same task.
And all those processes, by today's standards, are very formalized.
And the students do it with hundreds of students.
Yes.
Was the YMCA, was it active?
in your day?
Yeah.
What went on there?
Logan Weston and Gay, Gordon Gay.
What did the, what happened at the one?
Mostly the reason you knew them is they had steak fries, you know, at Hensel Park.
And it was kind of a real thin kind of chicken fried steak like

thing but they there's no telling how many thousands of steaks that they cook at various functions or outfit functions or whatever whatever you wanted there was somebody you could go talk to of course it had that little gym up there before it was renovated in 79 and in the old days before the MSC it was the
had the swimming pool and the bowling alley, and it really was the student center from it being built until the MSC was built.
Now, Mr. Cashin had already died, hadn't he?
I didn't know him.
I don't remember him.
The folks older than you and I I've chatted with remember him.
H.L.
Heaton was the registrar.
Describe Mr. Heaton from your experiences.
An interesting little man that seemed very business-like, in a hurry, lots to do, kind of fidgety, I think, but would do whatever he was polite.
And when the general gave him an order, he followed it.
Well, as far as I know, they all did that.
Yes, but he particularly, I think, was...
Like I know privately, he said in my presence more than once, over my dead body will we ever have black students here.
Mr.
Rudder told him to check the credentials of all of those first black active duty enlisted men that were coming here to finish their degree to be sure that they were in the right courses.
He didn't want them to have to stand in line at Sabisa because there could be an incident there.
for Heaton to get them in the right courses, then call each instructor and tell them that when they met their first class, those students were supposed to be there.
Mr. Heaton.
Yes, sir.
And he did it.
What was Guyon Hole?
What role did it play?
Well, it was a gorgeous old building.
It was where you went to see old movies and the like.
It was very dilapidated.
When I came back was when they tore it down to start this facility over here.
And the architects screwed up.
They should have kept those columns.
Yes, yes, yes.
The front facade could have been, by today's standards, you would have saved it for sure.
